<!-- THE HOUSE ITSELF -->
<section class="fade-in">
  <div class="section-label">The Building</div>
  <h2>What is actually<br><em>being built</em></h2>
  <p>900 square feet plus loft. A simple rectangle — Portuguese farmhouse form — with a soul that is entirely Appalachian. Two interior doors. Everything else open. The walls are hemp. The surfaces are earth. The ceiling is wood. The floor is cork. The light comes from everywhere.</p>

  <h3>The Form</h3>
  <p>Approximately 24 x 38 feet. South-facing for maximum light and passive solar gain. Shed or simple gable roof with generous 2–3 foot overhangs protecting the earthen walls. Standing seam metal roofing. No basement. Vaulted ceiling in the main space rising to the ridge. Loft platform at 8–9 feet occupying roughly half the floor area, sleeping under the slope of the roof with a fixed skylight directly overhead.</p>

  <h3>The Wall Logic</h3>
  <p>Timber frame is the bones — local Appalachian hardwood posts and beams, rough-sawn with natural character. Hemp blocks are the body — laid like masonry around the frame, 8 inches thick at R-16, pre-cured and ready. Earthen plaster inside, lime render outside — the skin. No drywall anywhere. No siding. No house wrap. No synthetic materials in the wall assembly. The wall is complete in three natural layers.</p>

  <h3>Light & Openings</h3>
  <p>Large fixed glass windows on the south face — permanent, permanent light, deep hempcrete reveals that are one of the most beautiful features of a natural building. Operable casements on the east and west for cross-ventilation. Skylight over the loft. French doors off the bedroom to the screened porch. The windows that can be plastered partially in — thick plastered sills, deep frames — are not a compromise. They are an advantage.</p>

  <h3>Two Doors Only</h3>
  <p>One for the bedroom. One for the toilet room. Everything else — the kitchen, the bathroom shower and tub, the living space, the loft — flows as a single open volume. The shower at the edge of the living space, as in Costa Rica. The kitchen continuous with the dining and sitting. The loft open above. The bedroom the one private sanctuary, opening with French doors to the porch and through those to the screened sleeping space beyond.</p>

  <h3>The Cob Interior</h3>
  <p>The earthen plaster covers all wall surfaces. The cob builds up from there — the rocket mass heater surround as the visual and thermal anchor of the space, a built-in bench along one hempcrete wall, sculpted niches for books and objects and light, the deep window reveals shaped by hand. Mosaic pressed into soft plaster at the bathroom feature wall. The building becomes the art project while you live in it. There is no deadline on this work. It is the ongoing conversation between you and the building.</p>
